RAHOITUS.kieli_en#1: Non-citizens of Finland can get financial aid for studies in Finland if they live in Finland on a permanent basis for a purpose other than studying. This requires that they are registered as a permanent resident in the Finnish population register system. The purpose of residence in Finland is determined by reference to such matters as the residence permit, registration or acceptance to an educational institution. If you come to Finland solely for the purpose of attending a school, you cannot get Finnish student financial aid. For more information, see www.kela.fi.

The health centre is responsible for administering student healthcare. In accordance with the national health law the health centre shall administer, regardless of the student's domicile, student healthcare which shall comprise the monitoring of health conditions within an educational institute, student healthcare, medical care and dental care. ESTEETOMYYS.kieli_en#1:
Centria is actively involved in developing the accessibility of study and is a partner in the national ESOK.fi network (the network for accessible studies in institutes of higher education).

Centria strives to support and guide students‚Äô learning and professional development with proactive, well-organized and versatile aims. The whole personnel of Centria is engaged in study guidance. An important part of guidance is the tutoring system, involving both teachers and older students.

YLEISKUVAUS.kieli_en#1:
Unit of Kokkola-Pietarsaari, Social and Health Care Campus

The campus hosts students of both Centria University of Applied Sciences and Central Ostrobothnia Federation of Education. Having two educational organizations on the same campus makes the joint use of premises and equipment possible. The proximity of Central Ostrobothnia hospital and Kokkola Health Centre offers excellent opportunities for exchanging expertise.

More than 500 Centria students study on the campus in the degree programmes of Bachelor of Health Care and Bachelor of Social Services. The campus also houses a Bachelor of Health Care degree programme conducted in English and a postgraduate Master‚Äôs degree programme of Social and Health Care. The students represent many age groups and nationalities.

The campus offers good premises for teamwork and a student cafeteria Merikaisla.

KUSTANNUKSET.kieli_en#1: Studying for a university of applied sciences degree is free of charge, there are no tuition fees. The student is responsible for paying for such study expenses as books, devices and materials that are theirs to keep after graduation. The cost of living in Finland is on average comparable to the rest of Europe. It is crucial that you have taken care of your financial issues so that you can afford to stay in Finland even if you will not get any job during your studies. Basically, for expenses such as rent, food and personal costs, you will need approximately 560 Euros per month, that is 12 x 560 = 6 720 Euros for ONE year.
